<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Seed Starting Trays for Indoor Gardening</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    The best seed-starting tray is the one that gives seedlings enough root room and watering stability for the real indoor timeline — not just the ideal one.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, the best seed-starting trays are durable trays with enough cell depth, drainage, and root room to support healthy seedlings without forcing constant watering, crowding, or emergency potting-up.</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    Many gardeners choose trays mostly by cell count. The problem is that tray choice affects much more than how many seedlings fit under the lights.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tray size changes:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>how long seedlings can stay indoors comfortably</li>
    <li>how quickly trays dry out</li>
    <li>how forgiving the setup feels during spring delays</li>
    <li>how aggressively roots become crowded</li>
    <li>how often potting up becomes necessary</li>
    <li>how easy the trays are to manage under lights and shelves</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This matters especially for crops like peppers that often stay indoors longer and lose quality faster in cramped trays.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tomatoes can usually tolerate tighter schedules more easily, but even tomatoes decline quickly once roots become crowded or the transplant window slips.
  </p>

  <p>
    In practice, most tray problems come from underestimating the real indoor timeline rather than from choosing the “wrong” crop-specific tray.
  </p>
</header>

